The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                  
	Melbourne: Steve Waugh, Mark Taylor and Glenn McGrath will feature in a charity Twenty20 cricket match to raise funds for the Victorian bushfire sufferers.    
	Current Australian players David Warner, Nathan Bracken, Moises Henriques, women cricketers Lisa Sthelaker and Ellyse Perry, and former Test star Michael Slater will also feature in the game, to be called Australias Big Bash, at the Sydney Cricket Ground (SCG) on February 22.        
	Melbourne: Injury-prone Australian cricketer Shane Watson will train under Dennis Lillee to revive his career before the Indian Premier League (IPL) begins in April.    
	Watson is currently following a recovery plan for the stress fractures in his back and physiotherapist Victor Popov said the all-rounder will start bowling during the IPL.        
	Melbourne: Australian fast bowler Brett Lee is recovering from his injury faster than expected and is set for an early comeback to international cricket in the one-day series against Pakistan in April.    
	Sidelined with stress fractures in his foot since early last month, 32-year-old Lee was initially expected to return in the World Twenty20 to be held in England in June.        
	Chennai: Indian Armys Sivdhan came first in the 42 km race as hundreds of enthusiastic Chennaities participated in the seventh edition of the Chennai Marathon on Sunday.    
	Bibul Sugariya from Hyderabad and Nagendra Rao came second and third respectively.         
	San Jose: Rohan Bopanna and partner Jarkko Nieminen beat fourth seed Stephen Huss and Ross Hutchins 3-6, 7-6 (7-5), 10-5 to make the final of the $600,000 SAP Open in California.            
	London: Russia and Chelsea coach Guus Hiddink has said he plans to retire from football after the 2010 World Cup. I think I will quit in the summer of 2010 after the World Cup, Hiddink told an English daily.     
	From then on I am just going to ride around on my Harley-Davidson.          
	California: A horrendous front-nine marred Arjun Atwals card as he brought home a one-under 71 to slide six places to tied 33rd after the penultimate round of the AT amp;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am here.     
	India-born Swede Daniel Chopra, missed the cut after carding a one-over 73 in the third round.                                                                                                                                                                       
